 MacKenzie approaches international civil aviation as an arm of government policy: the extension abroad of Canadian national policy. He also looks at the relationship between the bureaucratic and political levels of government and, in the larger context, at the relations between Canada and its major allies, the United States and Great Britain. Drawing on private papers and government documents from Canada, the United States, Great Britain, and Ireland, MacKenzie offers an international perspective on one of Canada's most important contributions to public policy in the mid-twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAeronautics, CommercialxHistory. 0aAeronautics, CommercialxLaw and legislation. 0aAeronautics, CommercialzCanadaxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757630140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487576301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487576301.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK